The phrasing – “Consydre thou myne condicyon” – is a direct address, demanding immediate attention and reflection. The use of “thou” and “thy” creates a sense of intimacy and urgency, as if the speaker is appealing to a close confidante. It’s a deliberate attempt to bypass formality and connect with the recipient on a personal level.

Consydre thou myne condicyon;



“Reflecte upon myne fader” – this section shifts the focus to the father himself, urging the recipient to contemplate his plight. The word “fader” carries significant weight, implying a deep sense of filial piety and responsibility. It’s a call to recognize the father’s vulnerability and suffering.

Consydre thou myne condicyon;



The subsequent clauses – “Shall I forsake hym, when he is strycken wyth blyndnesse and destytute…” – articulate the speaker’s internal conflict. The father’s suffering – blindness and destitution – presents a significant challenge to the speaker’s ability to fulfill his obligations. “Strycken wyth blyndnesse” is a particularly evocative phrase, suggesting a profound loss of sight and independence.

Consydre thou myne condicyon;



“...to wrastle wyth infirmitie and penurye…” – this continues the description of the father’s hardships, highlighting his physical and financial struggles. “Wrastle” suggests a difficult and protracted battle against illness and poverty. “Penurye” underscores the depth of his financial distress.

Consydre thou myne condicyon;



“...when it lyeth wythin my poure to rendere hys latter yeeres fylled wyth comforte and joye?” – this concluding clause expresses the speaker’s desire to alleviate the father’s suffering. “Poure” indicates a limited capacity to provide assistance, while “rendere hys latter yeeres fylled wyth comforte and joye” reveals a profound longing for the father’s happiness in his final years.

